(1) (4 points) This problem deals with vector manipulations.

(1)(a) Create a vector that contains the following, in this order, and print the contents. Do not round off any values unless requested. * A sequence of integers from 0 to 6, inclusive. * Two repetitions of the vector c(2, -5.1, -23). * The sum of 7/42 and 3

#Bullet One
#Create a vector which contains sequence of integers from 0 to 6, inclusive of 0 and 6.
first_bullet  <- c(0:6)

#Bullet Two
#Create a vector which contains two repetitions of 2, -5.1, -23. Note the use of a repeater. 
second_bullet <- rep(c(2, -5.1, -23), times = 2)

#Bullet Three
#Create a vector which contains the sum of 7/42 and 3 without rounding.
thrid_bullet  <- c(7/42+3)

#Getting to the point, concatenate the bullet vectors to create "a vector".
vector_1a <- c(first_bullet, second_bullet, thrid_bullet)

#Print the resulting vector
print(vector_1a)
##  [1]   0.000000   1.000000   2.000000   3.000000   4.000000   5.000000
##  [7]   6.000000   2.000000  -5.100000 -23.000000   2.000000  -5.100000
## [13] -23.000000   3.166667

(2) (5 points) The expression y = sin(x) - cos(x) is a trigonometric function.

(2)(a) Using the trigonometric function above, write a function as defined by R in the proper format that accepts values for x and returns a value for y.

#Define an R function for the equation given above.
rFunction <- function(x){
  y <- sin(x) - cos(x)
  return(y)
  }

(2)(b) Create a vector, x, of 4001 equally-spaced values from -2 to 2, inclusive. Compute values for y using the vector x and your function in (a). Do not print x or y. Find the value in the vector x that corresponds to the minimum value in the vector y. In other words, restrict attention to only the values of x and y you have computed. Round to 3 decimal places and print the value of x you find and the corresponding maximum value for y.

Finding the two desired values can be accomplished in as few as two lines of code. Do not use packages or programs you may find on the internet or elsewhere. Do not print the elements of the vectors x and y. Use coding methods shown in the Quick Start Guide for R.

#Create a vector of 4001 equally-spaced values from -2 to 2, inclusive. 
vector_x <- seq(-2, 2, length.out = 4001)

#Create a vector of f(vector_x)
vector_y <- lapply(vector_x, FUN = rFunction)

#Print the value of x with the minimum value of y after rounding it to 3 decimal places.
print(round(vector_x[which.min(vector_y)], 3))
## [1] -0.785

(2)(c) Plot y versus x in color, with x on the horizontal axis. Show the location of the maximum value of y determined in 2(c). Add a title and other features such as text annotations. Text annotations may be added via text().

#Plot y = sin(x) - cos(x).
plot(vector_x, vector_y, pch=20, xlab = "x-values", ylab = "y-values", col.lab="gray35", cex = .25 , col = "cornflowerblue", main = list("y = sin(x) - cos(x)", cex = 1.5,
                  col = "cornflowerblue", font = 3))

#Plot minimum point.
points(vector_x[which.min(vector_y)], vector_y[which.min(vector_y)], col = "red", cex = 1, pch=19)

#Add text features.
text(vector_x[which.min(vector_y)], -1, col = "red", cex = 1, "Minimum y-Value")
text(vector_x[which.min(vector_y)], -1.21, col = "red", cex = 1, paste("(",round(vector_x[which.min(vector_y)],3),",",round(as.numeric(vector_y[which.min(vector_y)]),3),")"))

(3)(b) Girth is defined as the diameter of a tree taken at 4 feet 6 inches from the ground. Convert each diameter to a radius, r. Calculate the cross-sectional area of each tree using pi times the squared radius. Sort Radius ascending and print. Present the stem-and-leaf plot of the radius, and a histogram of the radius in color.

#Calculate the radius values for trees given the girth and store as a new variable in trees.
trees$Radius <- as.double(lapply(trees$Girth, function(x) x/2))

#Print the radius sorted in ascending order.
print(sort(trees$Radius, decreasing = FALSE))
##  [1]  4.15  4.30  4.40  5.25  5.35  5.40  5.50  5.50  5.55  5.60  5.65
## [12]  5.70  5.70  5.85  6.00  6.45  6.45  6.65  6.85  6.90  7.00  7.10
## [23]  7.25  8.00  8.15  8.65  8.75  8.95  9.00  9.00 10.30
#Present the stem-and-leaf plot of trees$Radius.
stem(trees$Radius)
## 
##   The decimal point is at the |
## 
##    4 | 234
##    5 | 34455667779
##    6 | 055799
##    7 | 013
##    8 | 0278
##    9 | 000
##   10 | 3
#Define a function that computes cross-sectional area. 
cs_area <- function(r){
  area <- pi*r^2 
  return(area)
  }

#Calculate the cross-sectional area of each tree using our new radius variable for each tree.
trees$Area <- as.double(lapply(trees$Radius, function(x) cs_area(x)))

#Present a histogram of the radius in color
require("RColorBrewer")
## Loading required package: RColorBrewer
hist(trees$Radius, main = "Frequency Distribution of Tree Radii", ylab = "Frequency of the Radii", xlab = "Radius of the Tree", col = c(brewer.pal(10, "Spectral")))

(4) (2 points) Use matrix operations shown in the Quick Start Guide to solve the following system of linear equations. Display the R script and the numerical solutions for x, y and z. Use matrix operations with your solution to reproduce the values 1, 1, 3 as a means of checking if your solution is correct. This last demonstration can be accomplished with matrix multiplication in one line of code. Print your result.

x - y + z = 1

x + y + z = 1

x + y - z = 3

#Setup our system of equations.
system_values <- c(1,1,3)
system_coefficients <- matrix(c(1, -1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, -1), nr = 3, byrow = T)

#Solve the system of equations.
solve(system_coefficients, system_values)
## [1]  2  0 -1
#Verify the solution
system_coefficients%*%(solve(system_coefficients, system_values))
##      [,1]
## [1,]    1
## [2,]    1
## [3,]    3
(5) (6 points) The Cauchy distribution is an example of a heavy-tailed distribution in that it will have (more) outliers in both tails. This problem involves comparing it with a normal distribution which typically has very few outliers.

5(a) Use set.seed(124) and rcauchy() with n = 100, location = 0 and scale = 0.1 to generate a random sample designated as y. Generate a second random sample designated as x with set.seed(127) and rnorm() using n = 100, mean = 0 and sd = 0.15.

Generate a new object using cbind(x, y). Do not print this object. Use apply() with this object to compute the inter-quartile range or IQR for each column: x and y. Round the results to four decimal places and present. (The point of this exercise is to demonstrate the similarity of the IQR values.)

For information about rcauchy(), use help in R (?rcauchy). Do not print x and y.

#Set seed and generate random sample with Cauchy distribution designated as y.
set.seed(124)
y <- rcauchy(n = 100, location = 0, scale = 0.1)

#Set new seed and generate second random sample with normal distribution designated as x.
set.seed(127)
x <- rnorm(n = 100, mean = 0, sd = 0.15)

#Combine Vectors.
cauchy_normal <-cbind(x,y)

#Compute IQR of each random sample.
cauchy_normal_IQR <-apply(cauchy_normal, 2, FUN = IQR)

#Print the IQR of each random sample.
print(round(cauchy_normal_IQR, 4))
##      x      y 
## 0.2041 0.2141

(5)(b) This item will illustrate the difference between a heavy-tailed distribution and one which does not have heavy tails. Use par(mfrow = c(2, 2)) to generate a display with four diagrams. On the first row, present two histograms in color, one for x and the second for y. Set xlim = c(-7, 7) for the Cauchy results, and xlim = c(-0.45, 0.45) for the Normal results. Do not specify ylim for the histograms. On the second, show vertical boxplots for x and y. Use the xlim interval values respectively for the ylim of the boxplots.

#Configure multi-plot.
par(mfrow = c(2, 2))

#Display histograms.
hist(y, main = "Histogram of y", xlim = c(-7, 7), ylab = "Frequency", col = c(brewer.pal(10, "Spectral")))
hist(x, main = "Histogram of x", xlim = c(-0.45, 0.45), ylab = NULL, col = c(brewer.pal(14, "Spectral")))
## Warning in brewer.pal(14, "Spectral"): n too large, allowed maximum for palette Spectral is 11
## Returning the palette you asked for with that many colors
#Display boxplots.
boxplot(y, main = "Boxplot of y", ylim = c(-7, 7), ylab = "Frequency", sub = "Cauchy Distribution", col="blue")
boxplot(x, main = "Boxplot of x", ylim = c(-0.45, 0.45), ylab = NULL, sub = "Normal Distribution", col="gold")

(5)(c) QQ plots are useful for detecting the presence of heavy-tailed distributions. Use par(mfrow = c(1, 2)) and present side-by-side plots, one for each sample, using qqnorm() and qqline(). Add color and titles. Use cex = 0.5 to control the size of the plotted data points.

#Configure multi-plot.
par(mfrow = c(1, 2))

#Plot qqnorm and qqline for Cauchy distribution.
qqnorm(y, main = "Q-Q Plot for y", sub = "Cauchy Distribution", cex = 0.5, col = "blue")
qqline(y, col = "red", lty = 2)

#Plot qqnorm and qqline for normal distribution.
qqnorm(x, main = "Q-Q Plot for x", sub = "Normal Distribution", ylab = "", cex = 0.5, col = "blue")
qqline(x, col = "red", lty = 2)
